This is a feature request. I am starting with an example. Suppose we have following c# file-
```csharp
using System;

namespace ExampleNamespace
{
    class ExampleClass
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
        }

        static void ExampleMethod1()
        {
            Console.WriteLine("ExampleMethod1");
        }

        static void ExampleMethod2()
        {
            var methodName = "ExampleMethod2";

            foreach(var c in methodName)
            {
                if(char.IsUpper(c))
                {
                    Console.WriteLine("Upper case");
                }
                else
                {
                    Console.WriteLine("Lower case");
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```
If we are browsing the file at the end, it looks something like this now-
![current](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/751732/26113648/f35eef8c-3a7c-11e7-8e9e-d52971278bb7.PNG)

And I want it look something like this when the feature is enabled-
![requested](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/751732/26113706/176d1dc2-3a7d-11e7-99eb-2e2ac0176a0b.PNG)

It means the parent syntax nodes of the area being browsed is automatically freezed, so that user can easily guess the context of the current code, regardless of how far the parent nodes are. Some new points being added-
- I think this should be a toggle to on/off feature and not a setting.
- And parent syntax nodes should smoothly stack up or goes out of stack while scrolling.
- This should be tied with the current viewport and not current cursor position in my opinion.
- For if-else chains and switch cases (previous) sibling nodes should also be included in the stack.
- This can be solely based on indentation instead of actual syntax tree of the language, just like current folding in vscode.
- There should be a minimum height of the viewport without parent nodes, with actual code, which may be half the height of full viewport. When that value will be reached (like for heavily nested code), furthest or top most parent nodes can be hidden in that order. The closes parent nodes will remain visible.
